  "signature": "ed25519:9b1d4e7a2f053c86d1e4b2a7f3c09d5e8b2a1f6d4c7e0b3a9f2d5c8e1b4a7f3c",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled FEA solver with documented release notes and regression test suite covering linear static and nonlinear contact problems relevant to implant mechanics.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 was used under a validated installation qualification (IQ) and operational qualification (OQ) protocol. Release notes document patch history; an internal regression suite of 47 benchmark cases was executed and passed prior to this study. All simulation scripts are stored in a Git repository with commit hashes recorded in the study record. Level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver code verified against at least two published analytical or manufactured solutions for structural mechanics problems involving contact and nonlinear material behavior.",
      "rationale": "The Ansys solver was verified against the Hertzian contact analytical solution and a Timoshenko beam bending benchmark with documented error less than 0.5% for both cases. These benchmarks are directly relevant to the contact-dominated pedicle screw–rod interface and the bending-dominated failure mode assessed in ASTM F1717. Level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating that QoI changes less than 5% between the penultimate and final refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation or GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "A four-level mesh refinement study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface region. Global element size was halved at each level (8 mm → 4 mm → 2 mm → 1 mm nominal). Stiffness QoI changed by 3.2% between levels 3 and 4; yield force changed by 2.8%. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) was computed as 1.7% for stiffness, confirming the solution is in the asymptotic range. The production mesh corresponds to level 3 with a 10% safety factor applied. Level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence criteria documented and shown to be below 1e-4 for all load steps; energy balance check performed.",
      "rationale": "Force and displacement residuals were monitored at each Newton–Raphson iteration with convergence tolerance set to 1e-5 (tighter than the criterion). Energy balance was verified: external work equals internal strain energy within 0.3% across all 11 model instances. No unconverged load steps were recorded. Level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs reviewed by a second analyst; boundary condition application documented and cross-checked against ASTM F1717 fixture geometry.",
      "rationale": "All model setup files were independently reviewed by a second FEA engineer who confirmed boundary condition placement, material assignments, and contact pair definitions against the ASTM F1717 standard fixture drawing. Discrepancies identified during review (one incorrect friction coefficient initial value) were corrected prior to production runs. The review is documented in the study record. Level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model and contact formulation justified by literature or prior validation; sensitivity of QoI to model form assumptions quantified.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy Ti-6Al-4V was modeled using a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model with parameters from ASTM E8 tensile coupon data supplied by the device manufacturer. Augmented Lagrangian contact with a Coulomb friction coefficient of 0.2 (literature-supported for Ti-Ti interfaces) was used at the screw–rod interface. A one-factor-at-a-time sensitivity study showed that a ±50% variation in friction coefficient changed stiffness QoI by less than 4%, confirming low sensitivity to this assumption. Level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material and geometric inputs traceable to measured data; uncertainty in inputs propagated to QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs were derived from coordinate measuring machine (CMM) measurements of three representative screws and rods from the production lot, with dimensional variability characterized. Material elastic modulus and yield strength were taken from manufacturer-supplied tensile test certificates (n=5 coupons per lot). A Monte Carlo propagation (1000 samples) of dimensional and material uncertainty yielded a QoI uncertainty band of ±4.1% for stiffness and ±5.3% for yield force, both within the 10% acceptance bound. Level 3 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens are production-representative; sample size sufficient to characterize experimental variability; lot traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were drawn from a single production lot with full dimensional inspection records. The coefficient of variation for stiffness across N=11 was 4.8%, indicating acceptable production consistency. Sample size analysis confirmed that N=11 provides 80% power to detect a 10% QoI difference at α=0.05. Lot traceability is documented. Level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios, including at least two distinct load magnitudes or configurations, with environmental conditions (temperature, lubrication) controlled and documented.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single load configuration: quasi-static compression-bending at room temperature with no simulated physiological fluid. The standard protocol was followed with high fidelity, and inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed (coefficient of variation < 3% between labs). The team notes that the ASTM F1717 protocol is the regulatory gold standard and has been applied consistently in over 200 published pedicle screw validation studies. Furthermore, prior internal cyclic fatigue testing of the same construct geometry under a separate protocol demonstrated robust performance across a range of load magnitudes, providing indirect confidence that the single-condition static test is representative of the construct's mechanical envelope. Expert biomechanical judgment, supported by the FDA guidance on spinal implant testing, indicates that compression-bending at the standard offset is the governing load case for this device class. While only one test condition was employed in this specific validation activity, the convergence of regulatory precedent, inter-laboratory agreement, and supplementary fatigue data was considered sufficient to support the overall credibility argument. Nonetheless, the formal achievedLevel is recorded as 2 because a second distinct load configuration was not included within the scope of this validation activity."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs match experimental conditions within documented tolerances; any discrepancies between nominal and as-tested values are quantified and their effect on QoI bounded.",
      "rationale": "As-tested screw insertion torque, rod pre-bend angle, and fixture offset distance were recorded for each specimen and used to update the corresponding FEA model instance. Maximum deviation between nominal and as-tested geometric parameters was 0.3 mm for offset distance and 1.2° for rod angle. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that these deviations shift stiffness QoI by less than 1.5%. All 11 FEA instances used specimen-specific input values. Level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E/uval) computed for each QoI; all metrics within pre-specified acceptance bounds.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement across all 11 specimen-specific model instances. Maximum E/uval was 1.41 (stiffness, specimen 7), well below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Percent differences ranged from 0.8% to 8.3%, all within the 10% bound. Bland–Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias. Acceptance bounds were defined prior to data unblinding per the study protocol. Level 3 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly correspond to clinically and regulatorily relevant performance endpoints; linkage to device failure modes documented.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the primary endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA's 2021 guidance on spinal implant submissions. Stiffness governs load sharing with the spine; yield force is the threshold for permanent deformation leading to loss of fixation; force at 40 mm is a surrogate for post-yield energy absorption. All three are directly linked to the dominant failure mode (screw fatigue fracture following plastic deformation) identified in the device risk analysis. Level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and material; any extrapolation beyond the validation domain is bounded and justified.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw geometry, Ti-6Al-4V material, and ASTM F1717 test configuration as specified in the COU. No geometric or material extrapolation is required. The FEA model ensemble was not applied to any configuration outside the tested domain. The two-laboratory design provides additional assurance that the validation result is not laboratory-specific. Level 3 is satisfied."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 credibility factors. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required level. The single shortfall — Test conditions at achievedLevel 2 against a requiredLevel of 3 — was considered in the context of the overall evidence package. The team noted that ASTM F1717 is a single-condition protocol by design, that inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed across two independent facilities, and that supplementary fatigue data from a separate internal study provides indirect confidence in the representativeness of the static compression-bending configuration. The governing QoIs are all within acceptance bounds (maximum E/uval 1.41, maximum percent difference 8.3%), and no systematic bias was identified. The model risk level of 3 (Medium-High) is consistent with a Medium assurance level given the regulatory context and the direct nature of the validation comparison. Taking the totality of evidence into account — strong quantitative agreement, high relevance of QoIs, specimen-specific model instances, and regulatory precedent supporting the single-condition test — the team concluded that the overall credibility of the FEA model for this COU is sufficient to support regulatory submission. The package is therefore Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
